The article discusses the meeting between President Barack Obama and Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos at the White House. The meeting commemorated 15 years of bilateral cooperation through Plan Colombia and celebrated Colombia's political, economic, and security gains since the inception of the program. The article highlights the success of Plan Colombia in reducing violence and improving the economy in Colombia. It also mentions the ongoing peace negotiations with the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) and the support of the United States in achieving a lasting peace accord. The article introduces a new framework for bilateral cooperation called Peace Colombia, which aims to support Colombia in consolidating and expanding progress on security, counternarcotics, and reintegrating the FARC into society. The article also discusses the Global Demining Initiative for Colombia, in which the United States and Norway will provide funding to help Colombia become mine-free by 2021. Additionally, the article mentions the collaboration between the United States and Colombia in fighting the Zika virus, including sharing epidemiologic data and conducting joint research. It emphasizes the importance of regional and multilateral cooperation to combat Zika and other mosquito-borne diseases.